@author:
The spark UDF test (`pytest tests/pyfunc/test_spark.py::test_spark_udf --large`) was failing due to leaked mlruns directory from another test run (we should fix that separately), see [this travis log](https://travis-ci.org/mlflow/mlflow/jobs/562924587). The failure revealed that we currently have a bug/edge case in how we handle downloading artifacts from empty directories (in ArtifactRepository.download_artifacts, we assume that an empty result from list_artifacts implies that an artifact path is a file, but it could actually be an empty directory, e.g. the `mlruns` directory in the above failure). I changed this code to get the test to pass on the PR, but this is probably not the right solution (will think about this more tomorrow)

@user1:
I don't understand why do you want to add the list_dir to the result. Can you elaborate on what caused the error and how does this fixes it? From looking at it briefly I don't think the list_dir should be returned. If anything, I don't understand why list artifacts pointing to a file does not return the file itself. 

@author:
Yeah agreed, adding `list_dir` is just a hack to get the tests to pass against the file-based artifact repo, because it allows us to distinguish between listing an empty directory & a file.

Agree that it'd make sense for list_artifacts pointing a file to return the file itself (similar to how `ls` behaves), but that's a broader change that requires modifications across the different artifact repository implementations, so I just worked around this for now by removing the problematic empty `mlruns` directory in the `projects` tests that create it.
